Recently, anamorphic cryptography became a rapidly developing branch of covert information channels technology. The novel feature is that such channels remain undetectable even if the (official) user keys are surrendered to an auditor. Rejection Sampling is the most universal technique for creating such channels, applicable to most protocols used in practice. On the downside, its bandwidth is practically limited to a few bits, while randomized execution time may enable channel detection via side-channel analysis. To some extent, we eliminate these limitations by applying smart Advance Sampling with a relatively small dynamic lookup table (LUT). Even though the entries in LUT are produced and consumed at random, we keep LUT stable by using a symmetric power-of-two-choices strategy for insertion and removal. Contrary to the classical Rejection Sampling, the computation time of Advance Sampling is constant, while the bandwidth of the covert channel increases substantially. For example, a 16-bit covert channel can be achieved without a slowdown of order 215. Due to the improved bandwidth, Advance Sampling can be used as a pragmatic protection against quantum threats. In particular, it may be utilized to “fish out” most signatures forged by an adversary with compromised keys.